title: Simplify UnpackInitializerData API
body:
**Description**: Simplify UnpackInitializerData API

**Motivation and Context**
- There are crashes reported due to unaligned memory access on arm, such as https://github.com/onnx/onnx/pull/3626, and #2813, there are many places in our mobile EP code still access the initializer data directly, which may cause issue later
- Plan is to move all the EP code accessing initializer data directly to use UnpackInitializerData
- This change is to simplify the API of UnpackInitializerData, to use std:vector instead of a pair of std::unique_ptr for data and a size_t for size, also add one extra UnpackInitializerData to work on internal initializer only (return error when it is used on tensor with external data)
  *  The only disadvantage of using vector is that the memory need to be initialized, which may have slight perf hit while creating session
- There will be on extra change to update all the EP code, one typical update is at `onnxruntime/core/providers/shared/utils/utils.cc`

title: Fix Windows Store build
body:
Reopening #8481 with extra fixes for the DML adapter.

**Description:** Remove APIs unavailable in Store and a build break from #8349, #8178, #8065

Also remove workaround that was needed for WRL and flatbuffers to compile (expose all Desktop-only symbols). Previously there were a ton of missing symbols when targeting UWP and now there's only one in flatbuffers, so I'm replacing it with a more restricted workaround (stub of the missing C++ runtime function).

This change sets the proper Windows family macros that hides unsupported symbols in the Windows headers (e.g. the Windows headers don't expose Desktop-only symbols if the family is set to universal app). This should hopefully turn some recurrent runtime issues (accidentally adding Desktop-only symbols) into build breaks.

A workaround to [this old, known bug](https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/2790/files#r363957058) is also included: precompiled headers were being written to a `<source name>.cpp` file, and we had multiple PCHs called pch.h being saved to pch.cpp. This leads a race and compilation errors (access denied when trying to write a file concurrently) when building targets in parallel, especially with Ninja.

body:
**Describe the bug** & **To Reproduce**
I would like to use ML.NET on my Jetson Nano to run a ONNX model. The NuGet does not seem to include the ARM64 library and CUDA bindings so I tried to do this myself.

Script run on my Jetson host:
```bash
git clone --depth 1 --branch v1.8.0 --recursive https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime.git
cd onnxruntime
./build.sh --update --config MinSizeRel --build --parallel --use_cuda --skip_tests --cuda_home /usr/local/cuda --cudnn_home /usr/lib/aarch64-linux-gnu
```

This completes with `libonnxruntime_providers_cuda.so`, `libonnxruntime_providers_shared.so` and `onnxruntime.so` in the `~/onnxruntime/build/Linux/MinSizeRel` folder.

Then I create new .NET Console app (on the Jetson host, where I installed the .NET 5.0 SDK):
```xml
<Project Sdk="Microsoft.NET.Sdk">
  <PropertyGroup>
    <OutputType>Exe</OutputType>
    <TargetFramework>net5.0</TargetFramework>
  </PropertyGroup>
  <ItemGroup>
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime" Version="1.8.0" />
    <PackageReference Include="Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime.Managed" Version="1.8.0" />
  </ItemGroup>
</Project>
```

```cs
using System;
using Microsoft.ML.OnnxRuntime;

var inference = new InferenceSession("yolov3-10.onnx", SessionOptions.MakeSessionOptionWithCudaProvider());
```
When I then run:
`LD_LIBRARY_PATH=~/onnxruntime/build/Linux/MinSizeRel dotnet run`

title: [Dup] Fix SAME_UPPER/SAME_LOWER (auto_pad attribute) in ConvTranspose
body:
**Description**:
Dup of https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/pull/5368/.

To sync the definition of SAME_UPPER/SAME_LOWER among all operators and make it same as ONNX definition, switch the logic of SAME_UPPER and SAME_LOWER in ConvTranspose.

Definition of SAME_UPPER and SAME_LOWER should be as follows:
```
if auto_pads == 'SAME_UPPER':
  pad_head = paddings / 2  # smaller one 
  pad_tail = paddings - paddings / 2  # larger one
elif auto_pads == 'SAME_LOWER':
  pad_head = paddings - paddings / 2  # larger one
  pad_tail = paddings / 2  # smaller one
```

**Motivation and Context**
The `auto_pad` attribute, `SAME_UPPER` and `SAME_LOWER` of `ConvTranspose` is different from other operators' (pool and conv related operators) `auto_pad` attribute. The behavior of same attribute should be the same among all operators. Also, it does not meet the definition in ONNX.

- `SAME_UPPER` and `SAME_LOWER` in other operators
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/c20fcf26ebc0eeda41b6fd4e54d87623030ead91/onnxruntime/core/providers/cpu/nn/pool_attributes.h#L149
- ConvTranspose definition in ONNX:
https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/b2ed660d0a065b8346816f2c3a95d79ca79b88c9/onnx/defs/nn/defs.cc#L1222
- A related PR in ONNX (There is a contradiction of this in ONNX):

title: IsNaN and Split have no double implementations

**Is your feature request related to a problem? Please describe.**
IsNaN and Split operators raise not implemented error when passed a double tensor as input.

**System information**
- ONNX Runtime version (you are using):
v 1.7.2

**Describe alternatives you've considered**
Currently, to circumvent this, all double tensors are cast to float before they enter IsNaN and Split and cast back to double after. This is not an ideal solution because we lose precision this way.

title: TensorRT EP high memory consumption

labels.name: ep:TensorRT
labels.description: issues related to TensorRT execution provider

labels.name: stale
labels.description: issues that have not been addressed in a while; categorized by a bot

body:
Hi ONNXRT team,

We are trying to lower the memory consumption especially for TensorRT execution provider.

We tested two approaches:

The first is original FP 32 NN model but FP16 inference enabled for TensorRT.

- MEMORY: We did not observe any significant change in memory consumption when the caching was disabled. Only with the TRT engine file caching enabled we were able to save up to 700 MB of memory.
- INFERENCE PERF: For some NN models the inference performance has improved 2 times.
- NN MODEL LOAD: However, the load/compilation of the NN model is 4-5 times slower.

Second approach was converting the ONNX model to FP16 using a script provided in ticket #8173 (https://github.com/microsoft/onnxconverter-common/blob/master/onnxconverter_common/float16.py#L88) and testing both FP32 and FP16 inference.

- MEMORY: There is no difference in memory usage when using FP 16 model.
- INFERENCE PERF: The inference performance has decreased significantly with FP16 model.
- NN MODEL LOAD: The FP16 ONNX model load/compilation is much slower comparing to original FP32 model.

Do you have any advise for us how to save memory when using CUDA and TRT?

Thank you in advance.
Best Regards

title: revert cmake policy CMP0104 to OLD behavior for handling CMAKE_CUDA_ARCHITECTURES
body:
The if block under
https://github.com/microsoft/onnxruntime/blob/c117ac57b75735edfbbb57159371f6742405c9d1/cmake/CMakeLists.txt#L1487
never gets executed because of cmake policy CMP0104
cmake detects the cuda arch on the build system and select a default value for CMAKE_CUDA_ARCHITECTURES. 
Thus if(NOT CMAKE_CUDA_ARCHITECTURES) will always be false.

setting CMP0104 to OLD reverts to old behavior where CMAKE_CUDA_ARCHITECTURES is not set unless the user defines it.

title: Auto forward non method attribute lookups to the user's model and bind custom methods to ORTModule
body:
This pull request:
1. For non methods attributes: auto forwards any call made to the user's original *```torch.nn.Module```* through ```ORTModule``` by implementing the methods:
   - ```__getattr__```: Implemented for attribute lookups that could not be found in ```ORTModule``` and so a lookup is performed on the user's ```torch.nn.Module```.
   - ```__setattr__```: Implemented so that users can set attributes on their original module with ease. All attributes are set on the user provided module instead of on ```ORTModule```. This is also used as a way to signal to ```ORTModule``` that the execution graph has changed and therefore a re-export must be done before the next forward call. This is done automatically by this implementation. The auto re-export can be controlled by enabling the skip check for re-building the graph, re creating the execution agent and so on (```export ORTMODULE_SKIPCHECK_POLICY="SKIP_CHECK_BUILD_GRADIENT|SKIP_CHECK_EXECUTION_AGENT"```).
2. For methods attributes: copies user defined methods and binds them to the ```ORTModule``` instance. This is done in order to prevent the problem where user defined methods invoke the forward on the model thereby calling the `PyTorch` module implementation of forward as opposed to ```ORTModule```'s implementation of forward.

Users can now seamlessly use their training script with ```ORTModule``` without needing to change how they invoke user defined methods on their original ```torch.nn.Module```. Here is an example:
```py
# User defined torch.nn.Module 
class UserDefinedMethodsNet(torch.nn.Module): 
    def __init__(self): 
        super(UserDefinedMethodsNet, self).__init__() 

    def forward(self, ...): 
        ... 

    def custom_user_method(self, ...): 
        return some_calculation()  

    def training_step(self, ...):
        out = self(...)
        ...

# Instantiation of ORTModule 
model = UserDefinedMethodsNet() 
model = ORTModule(model) 

# Invoke user defined function 
out = model.custom_user_method() # No AttributeError since ORTModule auto forwards the call to the original module 
model.training_step(...) # ORTModule's forward will be executed and not the user defined forward
```

In addition, ```ORTModule``` checks for any attribute name collisions between the user's model and ```ORTModule```.

**Description**:
This adds the Gemm op to the DNNL Execution provider

With the addition of the Gemm op that uses the DNNL endpoint the KernelRegistry was deleted. The only Op that was in the KernelRegistry was Gemm and the implementation was not using DNNL.

Added two new tests one that only modifies the `alpha` attribute of Gemm another that only modified the `beta` attribute of Gemm.  This enabled figuring out which of the two attributes caused an issue.

Fix a few other bugs discovered while working on the Gemm op.

labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

body:
**Description**: Describe your changes.
_External custom ops_: Unlike custom operations defined in the onnxruntime code base, the external custom op schemas are compiled into a shared library independently and loaded at runtime. The user should be able to create and use custom ops using prebuilt onnxruntime. The user doesn't need to build onnxruntime to use the external custom ops.

This feature allows the user to directly specify custom op schemas in C/C++ and compile the code into a shared library that may be loaded into python script. See onnxruntime/orttraining/orttraing/test/external_custom_ops for example.

The custom ops need to register with registry in onnxruntime. In order to enable resolving onnx::* and protobuf::* symbols at load-time, onnxruntime needs to expose these symbols. The user code containing custom op schemas may be compiled using the ONNX header files bundled in the onnxruntime wheel. In addition to generated ONNX header files, the wheel contains Protobuf header files.

This PR doesn't add ORT API header files to onnxruntime wheel.

The current changes only support the use-case on Ubuntu platform. This feature requires building onnxruntime with --enable_external_custom_op_schemas and the code changes in this PR are guarded by this flag.

For more details please refer to https://microsoft-my.sharepoint.com/:w:/p/sajandhy/EbwOyIuMyUBEntJYYbjDLtoBDl53eNXlqKV4vfGxNBXb9A
**Motivation and Context**
This use-case is required for 1P users
- Why is this change required? What problem does it solve?
This change enables user to define operator schemas, compile and load into onnxruntime.

title: Performance degradation when a model fully fall backs to MLAS from an EP

body:
**Components**
->This analysis was w.r.t OpenVINO Execution Provider vs MLAS
-> Model used was mlperf_ssd_mobilenet_300 onnx model
-> Tool used to run the model: onnxruntime_perf_test
-> Platform: Linux (ubuntu)

**Describe the bug**
When I tried running this model with OpenVINO-EP. This model is not fully supported on openvino-ep for CPU device and so 0 subgraphs can run on OpenVINO-EP. Now, the whole model falls back completely to default MLAS - CPU Execution Provider.

what I observe is, there is a significant performance difference when this model is ran using OpenVINO-EP vs MLAS. Point to keep in mind is that even in OpenVINO-EP case, the model is still running with MLAS as the whole model was falling back to default MLAS.

**default CPU: (OnnxRuntime Optimizations are enabled by default)**
Total inference requests: 100
Total inference run time: 1.43431 s

**command:**
./onnxruntime_perf_test -r 100 -c 1 -e cpu mlperf_ssd_mobilenet_300/ssd_mobilenet_v1_coco_2018_01_28.onnx

**OV-EP CPU_FP32 Route: (OnnxRuntime Optimizations are enabled by default)**
Total inference requests: 100
Total inference run time: 3.38388 s

**command:**
./onnxruntime_perf_test -r 100 -c 1 -e openvino mlperf_ssd_mobilenet_300/ssd_mobilenet_v1_coco_2018_01_28.onnx

The reason why there is difference in performance timings though both were eventually running on MLAS is because of the early extra optimizations that are added when a model is run directly by MLAS.

**case 1:** You run a model directly using MLAS (CPU Execution Provider). Before going to inference stage, it introduces early ONNX optimizations like reshape_fusion and more. This influences the performance numbers during the final inference for the same 100 iterations we use.

**case 2:** You try running a model using OpenVINO-EP CPU. Then in get_capability stage, it realizes, it can't support any subgraphs on OV-EP. so the whole model has to fall back to default CPU provider (MLAS). It does fall back and is executed by MLAS. But here those early optimizations are not introduced over the model network from ONNXRuntime. since it came through OV-EP route and then had to fall back to default CPU route.

Refer the 2 logs attached in the ticket to prove the above analysis.

I also tried running this model by disabling onnxruntime optimizations which are usually enabled by default. Then I see similar performance in both cases.

**OV-EP CPU_FP32 Route: (Disabling onnxruntime optimizations)**
Total inference requests: 100
Total inference run time: 3.86726 s

**command:**
./onnxruntime_perf_test -r 100 -c 1 -o 0 -e openvino mlperf_ssd_mobilenet_300/ssd_mobilenet_v1_coco_2018_01_28.onnx

**default CPU: (Disabling onnxruntime optimizations)**
Total inference requests: 100
Total inference run time: 3.82465 s

**command:**
./onnxruntime_perf_test -r 100 -c 1 -o 0 -e cpu mlperf_ssd_mobilenet_300/ssd_mobilenet_v1_coco_2018_01_28.onnx


so, just wanted to understand. For the top scenario, where we are seeing significant difference in performance with optimizations enabled. If it's a bug or is it something expected? In the second scenario, with onnxruntime optimizations disabled, the performance is same in both cases (which is understood)

title: ORT Optimize constant folding remove needed node in Loop & If inner graph
body:
**Describe the bug**
Ort Optimize will remove some needed nodes in the inner graph, e.g: Loop Op and If Op. Here are 2 pictures to explain the before & after scenario for Loop & If.

Loop node here remove **3380(terminal condition output)** and identity node in the **loop body**, make inner graph's assumption NOT correct, since[ onnx doc ](https://github.com/onnx/onnx/blob/master/docs/Operators.md#attributes-39) NEED the 1st output of loop body to be a terminal condition. 

If node here remove **3323** & constant node in **If-Then branch**, make the if & then branch has different number output.

![loop_before_after_ort_optimize](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/30483478/130560131-dc20889a-792a-4c28-bfd1-5e0651feee20.png)

![if_before_after_ort_optimize](https://user-images.githubusercontent.com/30483478/130560138-3696682a-c827-4f3c-86bb-6fd3e2b8483b.png)

**Urgency**
I can work around by writing back these missing nodes in inner graph, but I think it is actually an urgent issue since we need to ship our production model ASAP. This kind of hack thing is a little wired.

**System information**
- OS Platform and Distribution (e.g., Linux Ubuntu 16.04): Windows10
- ONNX Runtime installed from (source or binary): binary
- ONNX Runtime version: 1.8.1
- Python version: 3.8.8

**To Reproduce**
-  You can use this script to reproduce this problem for loop operator, [Reproduce script](https://github.com/lanhongvp/Ort_Info/blob/main/src/seq_loop.py) . I didn't create a mock model with **If operator**, but also need to notice **If operator also has this similar issue.**
- Original [model](https://github.com/lanhongvp/Ort_Info/blob/main/models/seq_loop.onnx)
- Optimized [model](https://github.com/lanhongvp/Ort_Info/blob/main/models/seq_loop_cf.onnx)

**Expected behavior**
Need to make sure all operators' inner graphs have the correct graph optimize behavior.

**Additional context**
These models I shared above can both pass the ORT, **BUT** in our compiler, we have the **assumption each graph's output MUST BE some node's output in this graph,** and will remove some unused value_info in each graph. If the ORT has done some optimization above for Loop & If, we will remove unused value_info in inner_graph, **and finally make ORT complain.**

```
# some code to explain the additional context

def remove_unused_valueinfo_in_graph(graph):
    all_node_outputs_names = set()

    for node in graph.node:
        node_output_names = {name for name in node.output}
        all_node_outputs_names = set.union(all_node_outputs_names, node_output_names)

   # assumption here means we assume each graph's output MUST BE some node's output in this graph
    for valueinfo in list(graph.output):
        if valueinfo.name not in all_node_outputs_names:
            graph.output.remove(valueinfo)

```

title: Optimize Concat and Split on CUDA to eliminate host-to-device copies when sizes are all the same

labels.name: training
labels.description: issues related to ONNX Runtime training; typically submitted using template

labels.name: core runtime
labels.description: issues related to core runtime

body:
This gives +14% end-to-end speed-up on [ProphetNet](https://github.com/microsoft/ProphetNet) model. This optimization is applied for the case all the tensors to be merged or split are the same size along the relevant axis. When there are few tensors (<=32), the tensor device addresses are passed as kernel arguments.

Invoking 4 host-device copy kernels on the default stream adds considerable overhead for the general case. A less urgent optimization would merge these into a single host-device copy. And yet another would avoid it altogether by passing all metadata as kernel arguments - but only if it fits within the 256 byte limit. These operations may further benefit from use of strided tensor formats.

title: Improve GenerateId to reduce hash collision

labels.name: stale
labels.description: issues that have not been addressed in a while; categorized by a bot

body:
We see hash collision when models have similar names and are in the same directory.
This PR improves GenerateId function by hashing nodes inputs/outputs besides model path.
1. hash model name instead of model path to address file moving issue.
2. repeat model name hashing to ensure enough characters are hashed and lower the chance of collision.
3. add flags to enable model name, nodes inputs/outputs hashing. It's off by default.
4. generalize GenerateId function to be used by MetaDef ID generator or model ID generator
